NOTE: The Tampa Bay Balloon Festival in that was mentioned in earlier versions of this list has changed its event dates to April 29-May 1. Tampa Bay AirFest: The gates to MacDill Air Force Base will open to the public with the U.S. Navy Blue Angels as headliners (3 p.m. both days). There will also be parachute jumps, aircraft to tour, vendors and an F-22 demo. This family-friendly event is packed with activities and showcases all branches of the U.S. military and local first responders. Gates open at 8 a.m., with opening ceremonies at noon. Free. $40-$600 VIP seating. 8 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday-Sunday. MacDill Air Force Base, 8208 Hangar Loop Drive, Tampa. 813-828-2351. Spring Training Games: A shortened spring training season is underway. Here’s a look at the schedules for the Tampa Bay Rays and some other teams: Hollywood Awards Night 2022: Hit the red carpet and chat with Roan Jivers about who you’re wearing at the 23rd annual Oscars watch party with paparazzi, costumed characters representing Hollywood bigwigs, photos, games, prizes, free popcorn, soda and live coverage of the Academy Awards. $25-$150. 6:30 p.m. Sunday. Tampa Theatre, 711 N Franklin St. 813-274-8680. Disney’s Frozen: The Tony-nominated Best Musical features the songs from the original film as well as a dozen new numbers. The play delves deeper into the theme of sisterly love. $40-$155. 7:30 p.m. Wednesday-Thursday, 8 p.m. Friday, 2 and 8 p.m. Saturday, 1 and 6:30 p.m. Sunday. David A. Straz Jr. Center for the Performing Arts, 1010 N MacInnes Place, Tampa. 813-229-7827. Steve-O: Bucket List Tour: Steve-O, who has made a multimedia comedy show out of his stunts, comes to Tampa. 18 and older only. $35-$100. 8 p.m. Thursday. David A. Straz Jr. Center for the Performing Arts, 1010 N MacInnes Place, Tampa. 813-229-7827. Tampa Pride: The city celebrates gay pride with parades and more. The following is a list of related events: Bruce Bruce: The performer and one-time host of BET’s Comic View, who has performed in some big-screen comedies, brings his improv skills and adult comedy to Tampa. $37-$47. 8 and 10:30 p.m. Friday, 7 and 9:30 p.m. Saturday, 7 p.m. Sunday. Tampa Improv, 1600 E Eighth Ave. 813-864-4000. Bay Area Renaissance Festival: Join the villagers of Fittlesworth in their 16th century European village with 15 stages of entertainment, with musicians, magicians, jugglers and jousting. There will also be vendors, a pub crawl, pony rides, birds of prey and a butterfly encounter. $19.95, $11.95 ages 5-12, 4 and younger free. 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturday-Sunday. 12838 Auton Road, Dade City. 800-601-4848. Chasco Fiesta: The 10-day festival with nightly entertainment, a carnival and a Native American Festival opens Friday. It is celebrating its 100th anniversary with a Roaring ‘20s-themed street parade on Saturday featuring floats, marching bands and krewes from across the state. Free. 1 p.m. Saturday. Main Street and Grand Boulevard, downtown New Port Richey. Find the full schedule and tickets for VIP seating at concerts at chascofiesta.com. Disney On Ice: Let’s Celebrate: The legacy of Disney is displayed through 14 classic and modern stories in this production with international award-winning figure skaters, high-energy choreography, more than 50 characters and 30 popular Disney songs. $20-$100. 7 p.m. Thursday-Saturday, 11 a.m. and 3 p.m. Sunday. Amalie Arena, 401 Channelside Drive, Tampa. 813-301-6500.  Midnight at the Masquerade: Attend the masquerade ball and help get this soiree back on track by trading clues with guests, gathering information and solving the crime before the masked menace gets away. Evening wear and Venetian masks encouraged. Benefits the Let’s Build a Story campaign. $35. 6-9:30 p.m. Friday. Safety Harbor Public Library, 101 Second St. N. 727-724-1525. Food From the Soul Festival: This food festival highlights African, African American, Asian, Caribbean, Hispanic/Latin/Latin X and Native American cultures and the origins of their food. There also will be music by local bands, wine pairings, face painting, a skate park and more. $25 (food/drink additional). 10 a.m.-4 p.m. Saturday. Perry Harvey Sr. Park, 1201 N Orange St., Tampa. 813-335-9887. Jackie Evancho: The 19-year-old whose eighth studio album features songs from musicals including Hamilton, Dear Evan Hansen and Waitress, as well as hit films like The Greatest Showman, performs. $49.50-$79.50. 7 p.m. Wednesday. Nancy and David Bilheimer Capitol Theatre, 405 Cleveland St., Clearwater. 727-791-7400. Murder on the Orient Express: An American tycoon lies dead in a train cabin that’s locked from the inside. With renowned detective Hercule Poirot leading the investigation, an eclectic group of suspects evade and deflect but ultimately can’t stop Poirot from identifying the killer. $35-$40. 8 p.m. Friday, 3 and 8 p.m. Saturday, 3 p.m. Sunday. Stageworks Theatre, 1120 E Kennedy Blvd., Tampa. 813-374-2416.